# Aggregates and Domain Invariants

Aggregates are clusters of domain objects (entities and value objects) treated as a single unit for data changes. The Aggregate Root is the single entity that external code may hold references to. Invariants are business rules that must always be true within an aggregate boundary.

## General Principles

- **Aggregates define consistency boundaries** - All business invariants must be maintained within a single aggregate
- **Only reference aggregates by ID** - Never hold direct references to entities inside other aggregates
- **One transaction per aggregate** - Modify one aggregate per transaction when possible
- **Keep aggregates small** - Prefer small, focused aggregates over large ones
- **Invariants must always be true** - Business rules must be enforced and validated

## Aggregates

### What is an Aggregate?

An aggregate is a cluster of related entities and value objects that form a **consistency boundary**. The aggregate is treated as a single unit for data modifications and maintains business invariants.

### Aggregate Root

The **Aggregate Root** is the single entity that serves as the entry point to the aggregate. External code may only hold references to the aggregate root, never to internal entities.

**Characteristics:**
- Only entity that can be referenced from outside the aggregate
- Responsible for maintaining invariants of the entire aggregate
- Controls access to child entities and value objects
- Used as the identifier for the entire aggregate

### ✅ CORRECT - Simple Aggregate with Root

```typescript
// Aggregate Root - Order
export class Order {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: OrderId,
    private readonly customerId: CustomerId,
    private readonly items: OrderItem[], // Child entities
    private readonly status: OrderStatus,
    private readonly totalAmount: Money,
  ) {}

  getId(): OrderId {
    return this.id
  }

  // ✅ Aggregate root controls access to children
  getItems(): ReadonlyArray<OrderItem> {
    return [...this.items]
  }

  // ✅ Aggregate root maintains invariants
  addItem(item: OrderItem): void {
    // Validate invariant: items must have positive quantity
    if (item.getQuantity() <= 0) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Invalid item quantity',
        400,
        'Order item quantity must be greater than zero',
        { itemId: item.getId().toString() },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    // Validate invariant: order total must not exceed limit
    const newTotal = this.calculateTotalWithItem(item)
    if (newTotal.isGreaterThan(Order.MAX_TOTAL_AMOUNT)) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Order total exceeded',
        400,
        `Order total cannot exceed ${Order.MAX_TOTAL_AMOUNT.toString()}`,
        { currentTotal: this.totalAmount.toString(), newTotal: newTotal.toString() },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    this.items.push(item)
    this.recalculateTotal()
  }

  // ✅ Business operation that maintains invariants
  cancel(): void {
    if (this.status.isCancelled()) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Order already cancelled',
        400,
        'Cannot cancel an already cancelled order',
        { orderId: this.id.toString() },
        ErrorCodes.INVALID_STATE
      )
    }
    // ... cancellation logic maintaining invariants
  }

  private recalculateTotal(): void {
    // ... recalculate total maintaining invariant
  }

  static readonly MAX_TOTAL_AMOUNT = Money.create(10000)
}

// Child Entity - OrderItem (only accessible through Order)
export class OrderItem {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: OrderItemId,
    private readonly productId: ProductId, // Reference to another aggregate by ID
    private readonly quantity: Quantity,
    private readonly price: Money,
  ) {}

  getId(): OrderItemId {
    return this.id
  }

  getQuantity(): Quantity {
    return this.quantity
  }

  getProductId(): ProductId {
    return this.productId // ✅ Reference to external aggregate by ID
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Violating Aggregate Boundaries

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Direct reference to child entity outside aggregate
export class Payment {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: PaymentId,
    private readonly order: Order, // ❌ NO - Should be OrderId
    private readonly amount: Money,
  ) {}
}

// ❌ WRONG - Direct reference to internal entity
export class Shipment {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: ShipmentId,
    private readonly orderItem: OrderItem, // ❌ NO - OrderItem is internal to Order aggregate
    private readonly address: Address,
  ) {}
}

// ✅ CORRECT - References by ID only
export class Payment {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: PaymentId,
    private readonly orderId: OrderId, // ✅ Reference aggregate root by ID
    private readonly amount: Money,
  ) {}
}
```

## Aggregate References

### ✅ CORRECT - References Between Aggregates by ID

When one aggregate needs to reference another, always use the aggregate root's ID, never a direct reference.

```typescript
export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: EventId,
    private readonly cityId: CityId, // ✅ Reference to City aggregate by ID
    private readonly categoryIds: CategoryId[], // ✅ Reference to Category aggregates by ID
    private readonly tagIds: TagId[], // ✅ Reference to Tag aggregates by ID
    // ... other properties
  ) {}

  // ✅ Access related aggregates through repositories, not direct references
}

// In use case:
@Injectable()
export class CreateEventUseCase {
  constructor(
    @Inject(EventRepository)
    private readonly eventRepository: EventRepository,
    @Inject(CityRepository)
    private readonly cityRepository: CityRepository,
  ) {}

  async execute(input: { cityId: CityId; /* ... */ }): Promise<Event> {
    // ✅ Load related aggregate if needed for validation
    const city = await this.cityRepository.findById(input.cityId)
    if (!city) {
      throw new OneJsError('City not found', 404, '...')
    }

    // Create event with ID references only
    const event = Event.create({
      cityId: input.cityId, // ✅ ID reference, not direct object
      // ...
    })

    return await this.eventRepository.save(event)
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Direct References Between Aggregates

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Holding direct reference to another aggregate
export class Event {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: EventId,
    private readonly city: City, // ❌ NO - Should be CityId
    // ...
  ) {}
}

// ❌ WRONG - Navigating through aggregate boundaries
export class UseCase {
  async execute(input: { eventId: EventId }): Promise<void> {
    const event = await this.eventRepository.findById(input.eventId)
    // ❌ NO - Accessing internal entities of another aggregate
    const cityName = event.getCity().getName() // ❌ NO - City is another aggregate
  }
}
```

## Domain Invariants

### What are Domain Invariants?

**Invariants** are business rules that must always be true. They represent constraints that must be enforced to maintain domain consistency.

**Key characteristics:**
- Must be enforced at all times
- Validated during entity/aggregate modifications
- Can involve multiple properties or entities within an aggregate
- Cannot be violated by business operations

### Where to Validate Invariants

1. **In Entity Methods** - When the invariant involves only that entity
2. **In Aggregate Root Methods** - When the invariant spans multiple entities within the aggregate
3. **In Domain Services** - When the invariant involves entities from different aggregates (rare)
4. **In Value Object Creation** - When the invariant is about the value itself

### ✅ CORRECT - Invariant Validation in Entity

```typescript
export class Order {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: OrderId,
    private readonly items: OrderItem[],
    private totalAmount: Money,
    private status: OrderStatus,
  ) {}

  // ✅ Invariant: Order total must equal sum of item totals
  addItem(item: OrderItem): void {
    // Validate item-level invariant
    if (item.getQuantity() <= 0) {
      throw new OneJsError('Item quantity must be positive', 400)
    }

    this.items.push(item)

    // ✅ Maintain aggregate invariant
    this.recalculateTotal()
    this.validateTotalInvariant()
  }

  // ✅ Invariant validation method
  private validateTotalInvariant(): void {
    const calculatedTotal = this.items.reduce(
      (sum, item) => sum.add(item.getSubtotal()),
      Money.zero()
    )

    if (!this.totalAmount.equals(calculatedTotal)) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Order total invariant violated',
        500,
        `Order total ${this.totalAmount.toString()} does not match items total ${calculatedTotal.toString()}`,
        { orderId: this.id.toString() },
        ErrorCodes.INVARIANT_VIOLATION
      )
    }
  }

  private recalculateTotal(): void {
    this.totalAmount = this.items.reduce(
      (sum, item) => sum.add(item.getSubtotal()),
      Money.zero()
    )
  }
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Invariant Validation Across Multiple Entities

```typescript
export class User {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: UserId,
    private readonly venues: Venue[], // Child entities
    private readonly role: UserRole,
  ) {}

  // ✅ Invariant: User can have max 5 venues if not premium
  addVenue(venue: Venue): void {
    // Validate aggregate-level invariant
    if (!this.role.isPremium() && this.venues.length >= User.MAX_VENUES_FOR_STANDARD) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Venue limit exceeded',
        400,
        `Standard users can have maximum ${User.MAX_VENUES_FOR_STANDARD} venues`,
        { userId: this.id.toString(), currentVenueCount: this.venues.length },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    // Validate venue-level invariant
    if (this.venues.some(v => v.getId().equals(venue.getId()))) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Duplicate venue',
        400,
        'User already has this venue',
        { userId: this.id.toString(), venueId: venue.getId().toString() },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    this.venues.push(venue)
  }

  static readonly MAX_VENUES_FOR_STANDARD = 5
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Invariant Validation in Domain Service

```typescript
// ✅ When invariant spans multiple aggregates, use domain service
@Injectable()
export class EventSchedulingDomainService {
  validateEventDoesNotOverlap(
    event: Event,
    existingEvents: Event[],
  ): void {
    // ✅ Invariant: Events in same venue cannot overlap
    const overlappingEvent = existingEvents.find(existing =>
      existing.getVenueId().equals(event.getVenueId()) &&
      existing.getStartDate().isBefore(event.getEndDate()) &&
      existing.getEndDate().isAfter(event.getStartDate())
    )

    if (overlappingEvent) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Event overlap',
        400,
        'Event overlaps with existing event at same venue',
        {
          eventId: event.getId().toString(),
          overlappingEventId: overlappingEvent.getId().toString(),
          venueId: event.getVenueId().toString(),
        },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Missing Invariant Validation

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - No invariant validation
export class Order {
  addItem(item: OrderItem): void {
    // ❌ NO - No validation of quantity
    // ❌ NO - No validation of order total
    this.items.push(item)
  }
}

// ❌ WRONG - Invariant validated too late
export class Order {
  addItem(item: OrderItem): void {
    this.items.push(item)
    // ❌ NO - Should validate before adding
    if (this.items.length > 10) {
      this.items.pop()
      throw new Error('Too many items')
    }
  }
}

// ❌ WRONG - Invariant validated outside aggregate
export class OrderUseCase {
  async execute(input: { orderId: OrderId; item: OrderItem }): Promise<void> {
    const order = await this.repository.findById(input.orderId)
    // ❌ NO - Invariant should be validated in Order.addItem()
    if (order.getItems().length >= 10) {
      throw new Error('Too many items')
    }
    order.addItem(input.item)
  }
}
```

## Consistency Patterns

### Transactional Consistency (Within Aggregate)

Within an aggregate, all changes must be **transactionally consistent**. All invariants must be maintained immediately.

```typescript
// ✅ All changes to Order aggregate happen in one transaction
@Injectable()
export class AddOrderItemUseCase {
  async execute(input: { orderId: OrderId; item: OrderItem }): Promise<Order> {
    return await this.prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
      const order = await this.orderRepository.findById(input.orderId, tx)
      if (!order) {
        throw new OneJsError('Order not found', 404)
      }

      // ✅ Aggregate maintains invariants transactionally
      order.addItem(input.item)

      // ✅ Save entire aggregate atomically
      return await this.orderRepository.save(order, tx)
    })
  }
}
```

### Eventual Consistency (Between Aggregates)

Between aggregates, consistency may be **eventual**. Use domain events to propagate changes across aggregates.

```typescript
// ✅ Event published to maintain eventual consistency
@Injectable()
export class CreateEventUseCase {
  async execute(input: CreateEventDto): Promise<Event> {
    // ✅ Modify one aggregate transactionally
    const event = Event.create({ ... })
    const savedEvent = await this.eventRepository.save(event)

    // ✅ Publish event for eventual consistency with other aggregates
    await this.eventBus.publish(new EventCreatedEvent(savedEvent.toEventDto()))

    return savedEvent
  }
}

// ✅ Handler maintains eventual consistency
@EventHandler(EventCreatedEvent)
async handle(event: EventCreatedEvent): Promise<void> {
  // Update related aggregates asynchronously
  await this.cityStatisticsService.incrementEventCount(event.data.cityId)
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Trying to Maintain Transactional Consistency Across Aggregates

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Trying to modify multiple aggregates in one transaction
@Injectable()
export class CreateEventUseCase {
  async execute(input: CreateEventDto): Promise<Event> {
    return await this.prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
      const event = Event.create({ ... })
      await this.eventRepository.save(event, tx)

      // ❌ NO - Modifying another aggregate in same transaction
      const city = await this.cityRepository.findById(input.cityId, tx)
      city.incrementEventCount() // ❌ NO - City is separate aggregate
      await this.cityRepository.save(city, tx)

      return event
    })
  }
}
```

## Aggregate Size Guidelines

### Keep Aggregates Small

**Prefer small, focused aggregates** over large ones:

- **Small aggregates** are easier to understand and maintain
- **Small aggregates** reduce locking and contention
- **Small aggregates** improve transaction performance
- **Small aggregates** make invariants easier to validate

### ✅ CORRECT - Small, Focused Aggregate

```typescript
// ✅ Small aggregate with clear boundary
export class Tag {
  constructor(
    private readonly id: TagId,
    private readonly name: TagName,
    private readonly slug: Slug,
  ) {}

  // ✅ Simple, focused invariants
  static create(dto: { name: string; slug: string }): Tag {
    const tagName = TagName.create(dto.name)
    const tagSlug = Slug.create(dto.slug)

    // ✅ Invariant: name and slug must be consistent
    if (tagName.toSlug() !== tagSlug.toString()) {
      throw new OneJsError(
        'Slug mismatch',
        400,
        'Tag slug must match name',
        { name: tagName.toString(), slug: tagSlug.toString() },
        ErrorCodes.VALIDATION_FAILED
      )
    }

    return new Tag(Id.generate(), tagName, tagSlug)
  }
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Overly Large Aggregate

```typescript
// ❌ WRONG - Aggregate too large, includes everything
export class EventAggregate {
  constructor(
    private readonly event: Event,
    private readonly venue: Venue, // ❌ NO - Venue should be separate aggregate
    private readonly city: City, // ❌ NO - City should be separate aggregate
    private readonly categories: Category[], // ❌ NO - Categories are separate aggregates
    private readonly organizer: User, // ❌ NO - User is separate aggregate
    private readonly attendees: User[], // ❌ NO - Too many references
  ) {}
}
```

## Repository Per Aggregate

### ✅ CORRECT - Repository for Aggregate Root

Repositories should work with aggregate roots, not individual entities or value objects.

```typescript
// ✅ Repository works with Order aggregate root
@Injectable()
export class OrderPrismaRepository extends PrismaRepository<'order'> {
  async findById(id: OrderId): Promise<Order | null> {
    const orderDto = await this.prisma.order.findUnique({
      where: { id: id.toString() },
      include: { items: true }, // ✅ Load entire aggregate
    })

    return orderDto ? Order.fromDto(orderDto) : null
  }

  async save(order: Order): Promise<Order> {
    // ✅ Save entire aggregate atomically
    const dto = order.toDatabase()
    await this.prisma.order.upsert({
      where: { id: dto.id },
      update: dto,
      create: dto,
      include: { items: true },
    })

    return order
  }
}
```

## Rules Summary

### ✅ DO

- Design aggregates with clear boundaries
- Use one aggregate root per aggregate
- Reference other aggregates only by ID
- Validate invariants within aggregate boundaries
- Maintain transactional consistency within aggregates
- Use domain events for eventual consistency between aggregates
- Keep aggregates small and focused
- Validate invariants in entity/aggregate methods
- Use domain services for invariants spanning multiple aggregates (rare)

### ❌ DON'T DO

- Don't hold direct references to entities in other aggregates
- Don't navigate through aggregate boundaries
- Don't modify multiple aggregates in one transaction
- Don't validate invariants outside aggregate
- Don't create oversized aggregates
- Don't expose internal entities of aggregates
- Don't skip invariant validation
- Don't validate invariants after state change

